# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: arnhem-land
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:arnhem-land/1804-risdon-cove-massacre] On 3 May 1804, three or possibly as many as six Aboriginal Tasmanians were killed and others wounded by approximately 75 colonists and soldiers of the New South Wales Corps stationed at the fledgling British settlement of Risdon Cove, Van Diemen's Land.
[src:arnhem-land/1804-risdon-cove-massacre] Although some details of the massacre have been debated, eyewitness evidence indicated that at least three Aboriginal corpses were accounted for when "a great many were slaughtered and wounded" by the soldiers and colonists.
[src:arnhem-land/1804-risdon-cove-massacre] In early May 1804, around 300 Aboriginal people from either the Oyster Bay (Paredarerme) or Big River nation gathered near the recently established British outpost at Risdon Cove on the Derwent River.
[src:arnhem-land/1804-risdon-cove-massacre] These men, women and children, approached the settlement whilst occupied on a kangaroo hunt.
[src:arnhem-land/1804-risdon-cove-massacre] Although some were upset by the presence of the colonists, there had been no widespread aggression.
[src:arnhem-land/1804-risdon-cove-massacre] The colonists and a detachment of soldiers from the New South Wales Corps stationed at the settlement mistakenly thought they were being attacked and under the orders of Lieutenant William Moore, the commanding officer at the time, launched three sorties against the native people.
[src:arnhem-land/1804-risdon-cove-massacre] The massacre of the gathered Aboriginal people began at 11 o'clock in the morning of 3 May 1804 and the final shot, a blast from a carronade, was heard in the neighbouring settlement of Hobart three hours later.
[src:arnhem-land/1804-risdon-cove-massacre] The soldiers and the colonists were armed with Brown Bess muskets, which could be reloaded and fired once every 20 seconds and be used in close-quarters fighting as a club.
[src:arnhem-land/1804-risdon-cove-massacre] In addition to the firearms, the soldiers were ordered to fire grape shot from a 12-pounder carronade (a short-barrel, heavy calibre naval cannon known to sailors as "the smasher") to disperse the Indigenous people.
[src:arnhem-land/1804-risdon-cove-massacre] The clergyman Robert Knopwood heard "roar of the cannon at Risdon at 2 p.m".
[src:arnhem-land/1804-risdon-cove-massacre] The 12-pounder carronade involved was one of two ordered to be salvaged from the ship HMS *Investigator*, by Governor Philip Gidley King and given to Lieutenant Bowen.
[src:arnhem-land/1804-risdon-cove-massacre] "There were a great many of the Natives slaughtered and wounded", according to Edward White, an eyewitness to the event.
[src:arnhem-land/1804-risdon-cove-massacre] Claiming to be the first to see the approaching Aborigines, he also said that "the natives did not threaten me; I was not afraid of them; (they) did not attack the soldiers; they would not have molested them; they had no spears with them; only waddies".
[src:arnhem-land/1804-risdon-cove-massacre] None of the colonists or soldiers were harmed during the massacre, while three Aboriginal Tasmanian bodies were recovered from the scene.
[src:arnhem-land/1804-risdon-cove-massacre] The colonists "had reason to suppose more were wounded, as one was seen to be taken away bleeding".
[src:arnhem-land/1804-risdon-cove-massacre] Reverend Knopwood was of the opinion that at least five or six had been killed.
[src:arnhem-land/1804-risdon-cove-massacre] It is also known that an infant boy about 2–3 years old whose parents had been killed in the slaughter was taken by Jacob Mountgarrett, the colony's surgeon.
[src:arnhem-land/1804-risdon-cove-massacre] The boy was brought into British colonial society and given the name Robert Hobart May.
[src:arnhem-land/1804-risdon-cove-massacre] Mountgarrett also obtained the corpse of one of the deceased Indigenous men and dissected it.
[src:arnhem-land/1804-risdon-cove-massacre] The skull and bones of this man were shipped to Sydney in two casks.
[src:arnhem-land/1804-risdon-cove-massacre] Five days after the massacre, the Lieutenant Governor of Van Diemen's Land, David Collins, ordered the closure of the Risdon Cove settlement.
[src:arnhem-land/1804-risdon-cove-massacre] While he moved the settlers to Hobart, Collins ordered the outpost's soldiers to be sent back to Sydney citing their lack of discipline as being troublesome for the colony.
[src:arnhem-land/1804-risdon-cove-massacre] Lieutenant William Moore was acquitted of any wrongdoing in a court martial in September 1804.
[src:arnhem-land/1804-risdon-cove-massacre] In 1809, he was promoted to the rank of captain in the 102nd Regiment.
[src:arnhem-land/1804-risdon-cove-massacre] Previously, he wrote, the indigenous people had "evinced the most friendly disposition" towards the newcomers.
[src:arnhem-land/1804-risdon-cove-massacre] In a 2022 publication, *Truth-Telling at Risdon Cove*, the authors claimed that Edward White, who gave important eye-witness testimony, was not actually present at the massacre.
[src:arnhem-land/1804-risdon-cove-massacre] The substance of the book has been described as being easily dismissed and the authors' claims have since been rejected.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Australian languages have historically been classified into numerous language families.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Despite the diversity of Australian languages, many linguists have considered for decades that most languages of the Australian continent, including Pama-Nyungan, are members of one higher-level family.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] A proto-language, Proto-Australian, was reconstructed for the first time in 2024.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Proto-Australian is dated to approximately 6,000 years before the present, much later than human habitation of Australia; how it spread across the continent, replacing earlier languages, is as yet unclear.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] There have always been some Australian languages excluded from larger groupings as language isolates; currently, Tiwi and the Tasmanian languages are considered unrelated to Proto-Australian.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Of the languages of the Torres Strait, Kala Lagaw Ya is a Pama-Nyungan language, while Meriam Mer is a Papuan language.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] At the start of the 21st century, fewer than 150 Aboriginal languages remained in daily use, with the majority being highly endangered.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] In 2020, 90 percent of the barely more than 100 languages still spoken are considered endangered.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Thirteen languages are still being acquired by children.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] The surviving languages are located in the most isolated areas.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Of the five least endangered Western Australian Aboriginal languages, four belong to the Western Desert grouping of the Central and Great Victoria Desert.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] In 2026 the most widely-spoken languages by Australian Aboriginal people are those whose origins post-date the colonisation of Australia; these languages include Australian Kriol, Australian Aboriginal English, and Light Warlpiri.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] The Indigenous languages of Australia number in the hundreds, the precise number being quite uncertain, although there is a range of estimates from a minimum of around 250 up to possibly 363.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] In 2020, 90 per cent of the barely more than 100 languages still spoken are considered endangered.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Yolŋu languages from north-east Arnhem Land are also currently learned by children.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Bilingual education is being used successfully in some communities.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Seven of the most widely spoken Australian languages, such as Warlpiri, Murrinh-patha and Tiwi, retain between 1,000 and 3,000 speakers.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Some Indigenous communities and linguists show support for learning programmes either for language revival proper or for only "post-vernacular maintenance" (Indigenous communities having the opportunity to learn some words and concepts related to the lost language).
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] The *National Indigenous Languages Survey* is a regular Australia-wide survey of the status of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander languages conducted in 2005, 2014 and 2019.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Total 47 languages, 42,300 speakers, with 11 having only approximately 100.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Most Australian languages are commonly held to belong to the Pama–Nyungan family, a family accepted by most linguists, with Robert M.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] For convenience, the rest of the languages, all spoken in the far north, are commonly lumped together as "Non-Pama–Nyungan", although this does not necessarily imply that they constitute a valid clade.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Dixon argues that after perhaps 40,000 years of mutual influence and only a few centuries of written records, it is no longer possible to distinguish deep genealogical relationships from areal features in Australia, and that not even Pama–Nyungan is a valid language family.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] However, few other linguists accept Dixon's thesis.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Hale describes Dixon's scepticism as an erroneous phylogenetic assessment which is "such an insult to the eminently successful practitioners of Comparative Method Linguistics in Australia, that it positively demands a decisive riposte".
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Johanna Nichols suggests that the northern families may be relatively recent arrivals from Maritime Southeast Asia, perhaps later replaced there by the spread of Austronesian.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] That could explain the typological difference between Pama–Nyungan and non-Pama–Nyungan languages, but not how a single family came to be so widespread.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Nicholas Evans suggests that the Pama–Nyungan family spread along with the now-dominant Aboriginal culture that includes the Australian Aboriginal kinship system.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] This Proto-Australian language, they concluded, would have been spoken about 12,000 years ago in northern Australia.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] In 2024, Harvey and Mailhammer published a book-length reconstruction of Proto-Australian.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] For a long time unsuccessful attempts were made to detect a link between Australian and Papuan languages, the latter being represented by those spoken on the coastal areas of New Guinea facing the Torres Strait and the Arafura Sea.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Foley noted lexical similarities between Robert M.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Dixon's 1980 reconstruction of proto-Australian and the East New Guinea Highlands languages.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Dixon, in the meantime, later abandoned his proto-Australian proposal.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] According to Claire Bowern's *Australian Languages* (2011), Australian languages divide into approximately 30 primary sub-groups and 5 isolates.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] In 1962, Arthur Capell gave his assessment of the origins and internal grouping of Aboriginal languages.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] He referred to many attempts having been made to link the Australian languages to other parts of the world, including the Dravidian languages of South India, those of the Andaman Islands, and African languages.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Unclassified groups occupying the bulk of Queensland and New South Wales.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] In 1967 Carl Georg von Brandenstein claimed that he had isolated and identified some sixty Portuguese language loanwords in several indigenous languages of Australia's far north.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Australian linguists have generally dismissed these conclusions, except perhaps for the word *tartaruga*.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Nick Thieberger, a Melbourne University linguist, argues that Brandenstein's approach was still strongly influenced by outdated nineteenth-century linguistic thinking.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] It has been inferred from the probable number of languages and the estimate of pre-contact population levels that there may have been from 3,000 to 4,000 speakers on average for each of the 250 languages.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] A number of these languages were almost immediately wiped out within decades of colonisation, the case of the Aboriginal Tasmanians being a notorious example.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Tasmania had been separated from the mainland at the end of the Quaternary glaciation, and Indigenous Tasmanians remained isolated from the outside world for around 12,000 years.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Claire Bowern has concluded in a recent study that there were twelve Tasmanian languages, and that those languages are unrelated (that is, not demonstrably related) to those on the Australian mainland.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] In 1990 it was estimated that 90 languages still survived of the approximately 250 once spoken, but with a high rate of attrition as elders died out.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Of the 90, 70% by 2001 were judged as 'severely endangered' with only 17 spoken by all age groups, a definition of a 'strong' language.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] On these grounds it is anticipated that despite efforts at linguistic preservation, many of the remaining languages will disappear within the next generation.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] The overall trend suggests that in the not too distant future all of the Indigenous languages will be lost, perhaps by 2050, and with them the cultural knowledge they convey.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] During the period of the Stolen Generations, Aboriginal children were removed from their families and placed in institutions where they were punished for speaking their Indigenous language.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Different, mutually unintelligible language groups were often mixed together, with Australian Aboriginal English or Australian Kriol language as the only lingua franca.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] The result was a disruption to the inter-generational transmission of these languages that severely impacted their future use.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Today, that same transmission of language between parents and grandparents to their children is a key mechanism for reversing language shift.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] There is some evidence to suggest that the reversal of the Indigenous language shift may lead to decreased self-harm and suicide rates among Indigenous youth.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Nya jawgar yaam Gumbayynggir.*" (Translation: My father is Dhunghutti.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] And, therefore, I am Gumbayynggir.) In the House of Representatives on 31 August 2016 Linda Burney gave an acknowledgment of country in Wiradjuri in her first speech and was sung in by Lynette Riley in Wiradjuri from the public gallery.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] 2019 was the International Year of Indigenous Languages (IYIL2019), as declared by the United Nations General Assembly.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] The commemoration was used to raise awareness of and support for the preservation of Aboriginal languages within Australia, including spreading knowledge about the importance of each language to the identity and knowledge of Indigenous groups.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Warrgamay/Girramay man Troy Wyles-Whelan joined the North Queensland Regional Aboriginal Corporation Language Centre (NQRACLC) in 2008, and has been contributing oral histories and the results of his own research to their database.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] As part of the efforts to raise awareness of the Wiradjuri language, a *Grammar of Wiradjuri language* was published in 2014 and *A new Wiradjuri dictionary* in 2010.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] The New South Wales *Aboriginal Languages Act 2017* became law on 24 October 2017 and established a board to advise on the preservation of Aboriginal languages that is known as the Aboriginal Languages Trust.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] It was the first legislation in Australia to acknowledge the significance of first languages.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] In 2019 the Royal Australian Mint issued a 50-cent coin to celebrate the International Year of Indigenous Languages which features 14 different words for "money" from Australian Indigenous languages.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] The coin was designed by Aleksandra Stokic in consultation with Indigenous language custodian groups.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] The work of digitising and transcribing many word lists created by ethnographer Daisy Bates in the 1900s at Daisy Bates Online provides a valuable resource for those researching especially Western Australian languages, and some languages of the Northern Territory and South Australia.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] The project is co-ordinated by Nick Thieberger, who works in collaboration with the National Library of Australia "to have all the microfilmed images from Section XII of the Bates papers digitised".
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] The project is succeeded by the Nyingarn Project , which digitises manuscripts and crowdsources transcriptions through DigiVol.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] In recent decades, there have been attempts to revive indigenous languages.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Significant challenges exist, however, for the revival of languages in the dominant English language culture of Australia.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] The Kaurna language, spoken by the Kaurna people of the Adelaide plains, has been the subject of a concerted revival movement since the 1980s, coordinated by Kaurna Warra Pintyanthi, a unit working out of the University of Adelaide.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] The language had rapidly disappeared after the settlement of South Australia and the breaking up of local indigenous people.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Ivaritji, the last known speaker of the language, died in 1931.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] However, a substantial number of primary source records existed for the language, from which the language was reconstructed.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] The Tasmanian Aboriginal Centre, in collaboration with the University of Tasmania and the wider Aboriginal community, is undergoing the process of reviving Traditional Tasmanian languages through the construction of *palawa kani* (trans.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] The *palawa kani* Language Program has been in the works since the early 1990s.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Due to the linguistic ethnocide of Aboriginal Tasmanians, *palawa kani* is the only Aboriginal language of Lutruwita/Tasmania today.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] "Some Aboriginal people distinguish between *usership* and *ownership*.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Whether it is due to genetic unity or some other factor such as occasional contact, typologically the Australian languages form a language area or *Sprachbund*, sharing much of their vocabulary and many distinctive phonological features across the entire continent.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] A common feature of many Australian languages is that they display so-called avoidance speech, special speech registers used only in the presence of certain close relatives.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] These registers share the phonology and grammar of the standard language, but the lexicon is different and usually very restricted.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] There are also commonly speech taboos during extended periods of mourning or initiation that have led to numerous Aboriginal sign languages.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] For morphosyntactic alignment, many Australian languages have ergative–absolutive case systems.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] These are typically split systems; a widespread pattern is for pronouns (or first and second persons) to have nominative–accusative case marking and for third person to be ergative–absolutive, though splits between animate and inanimate are also found.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] In some languages the persons in between the accusative and ergative inflections (such as second person, or third-person human) may be tripartite: that is, marked overtly as either ergative or accusative in transitive clauses, but not marked as either in intransitive clauses.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] There are also a few languages which employ only nominative–accusative case marking.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] The following represents a canonical 6-place Australian Aboriginal consonant system.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] It does not represent any single language, but is instead a simplified form of the consonant inventory of what would be found in many Australian languages, including most Arandic and Yolŋu languages.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] A typical Australian phonological inventory includes just three vowels, usually /i, u, a/, which may occur in both long and short variants.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] In a few cases the [u] has been unrounded to give [i, ɯ, a].
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] There is almost never a voicing contrast; that is, a consonant may sound like a [p] at the beginning of a word, but like a [b] between vowels, and either letter could be (and often is) chosen to represent it.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Australia also stands out as being almost entirely free of fricative consonants, even of the otherwise universal [s].
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] In the few cases where fricatives do occur, they developed recently through the lenition (weakening) of stops, and are therefore non-sibilants like [ð] rather than the sibilants like [s] that are common elsewhere in the world.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Some languages also have three rhotics, typically a flap, a trill, and an approximant (that is, like the combined rhotics of English and Spanish) and many have four laterals.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Besides the lack of fricatives, the most striking feature of Australian speech sounds is the large number of places of articulation.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Some 10-15% of Australian languages have four places of articulation, with two coronal places of articulation, 40-50% have five places, and 40-45% have six places of articulation, including four coronals.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] The four-way distinction in the coronal region is commonly accomplished through two variables: the position of the tongue (front, alveolar or dental, or retroflex), and its shape (apical or laminal).
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] There are also bilabial, velar and often palatal consonants, but a complete absence of uvular consonants and only a few languages with a glottal stop.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Both stops and nasals occur at all six places, and in many languages laterals occur at all four coronal places.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] A language which displays the full range of stops, nasals and laterals is Kalkatungu, which has labial *p, m*; "dental" *th, nh, lh*; "alveolar" *t, n, l*; "retroflex" *rt, rn, rl*; "palatal" *ty, ny, ly*; and velar *k, ng*.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Wangganguru has all this, as well as three rhotics.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Yanyuwa has even more contrasts, with an additional true dorso-palatal series, plus prenasalised consonants at all *seven* places of articulation, in addition to all four laterals.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Where vowels are concerned, it has 8 vowels with some morpho-syntactic as well as phonemic length contrasts (i iː, e eː, a aː, ə əː, ɔ ɔː, o oː, ʊ ʊː, u uː), and glides that distinguish between those that are in origin vowels, and those that in origin are consonants.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Kunjen and other neighbouring languages have also developed contrasting aspirated consonants ([pʰ], [t̪ʰ], [tʰ], [cʰ], [kʰ]) not found further south.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Descriptions of the coronal articulations can be inconsistent.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] The alveolar series *t, n, l* (or *d, n, l*) is straightforward: across the continent, these sounds are alveolar (that is, pronounced by touching the tongue to the ridge just behind the gum line of the upper teeth) and apical (that is, touching that ridge with the tip of the tongue).
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] This is very similar to English *t, d, n, l*, though the Australian *t* is not aspirated, even in Kalaw Lagaw Ya, despite its other stops being aspirated.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] The other apical series is the retroflex, *rt, rn, rl* (or *rd, rn, rl*).
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Here the place is further back in the mouth, in the postalveolar or prepalatal region.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] The articulation is actually most commonly subapical; that is, the tongue curls back so that the *underside* of the tip makes contact.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] That is, they are true retroflex consonants.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] It has been suggested that subapical pronunciation is characteristic of more careful speech, while these sounds tend to be apical in rapid speech.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Kalaw Lagaw Ya and many other languages in North Queensland differ from most other Australian languages in not having a retroflexive series.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] The first tends to be used in careful enunciation, and the last in more rapid speech, while the tongue-down articulation is less common.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Finally, the palatal series *ty, ny, ly*.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] (The stop is often spelled *dj*, *tj*, or *j*.) Here the contact is also laminal, but further back, spanning the alveolar to postalveolar, or the postalveolar to prepalatal regions.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] The tip of the tongue is typically down behind the lower teeth.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] This is similar to the "closed" articulation of Circassian fricatives (see Postalveolar consonant).
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] The body of the tongue is raised towards the palate.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] This is similar to the "domed" English postalveolar fricative *sh*.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Because the tongue is "peeled" from the roof of the mouth from back to front during the release of these stops, there is a fair amount of frication, giving the *ty* something of the impression of the English palato-alveolar affricate *ch* or the Polish alveolo-palatal affricate *ć*.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] That is, these consonants are not palatal in the IPA sense of the term, and indeed they contrast with true palatals in Yanyuwa.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] In Kalaw Lagaw Ya, the palatal consonants are sub-phonemes of the alveolar sibilants /s/ and /z/.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] These descriptions do not apply exactly to all Australian languages, as the notes regarding Kalaw Lagaw Ya demonstrate.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] However, they do describe most of them, and are the expected norm against which languages are compared.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Some have suggested that the most appropriate unit to describe the phonotactics of Australian languages is the phonological word.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] The optionality of CFIN is cross-linguistically normal, since coda consonants are weak or nonexistent in many languages, as well as in the early stages of language acquisition.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] The weakening of CINIT, on the other hand, is very unusual.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] No Australian language has consonant clusters in this position, and those languages with fortis and lenis distinctions do not make such distinctions in this position.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Place of articulation distinctions are also less common in this position, and lenitions and deletions are historically common here.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] While in most languages the word-initial position is prominent, maintaining all a language's contrasts, that is not the case in Australia.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Here the prominent position is C1(C2), in the middle of the word.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] C1 is typically the only position allowing all of a language's place of articulation contrasts.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Fortis/lenis contrasts can only occur at C1, or at C2 when C1 is a sonorant.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Consonant clusters are often restricted to the C1(C2) position, and are most commonly sonorant + obstruent sequences.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] In languages with pre-stopped nasals or laterals, those sounds only occur at C1.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Australian languages typically resist certain connected speech processes which might blur the place of articulation of consonants at C1(C2), such as anticipatory assimilation of place of articulation, which is common around the world.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] In Australia, this type of assimilation seems only to have affected consonants within the apical and laminal categories.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] There's little evidence of assimilation between the labial, apical, laminal, and dorsal categories.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Many proto-Pama–Nyungan /-np-/ and /-nk-/ clusters have been preserved across Australia.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Heterorganic nasal + stop sequences remain stable even in modern connected speech, which is highly unusual.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] The anticipatory assimilation of nasality is quite common in various languages around the world.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Typically, a vowel will become nasalized before a following nasal consonant.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] However, this process is resisted in Australian languages.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] There was a historical process in many languages where nasal + stop C1C2 clusters lost the nasal element if CINIT was a nasal.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Also, many languages have morphophonemic alterations whereby initial nasals in suffixes are denasalized if the preceding stem contains a nasal consonant.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] While the existence of phonemic pre-stopped nasals and laterals, contrasting with plain nasals and laterals, has been documented in some Australian languages, nasals and laterals are pre-stopped on a phonetic level in most languages of the continent.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] These phenomena are the result of a general resistance to the anticipatory assimilation of nasality and laterality.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] The lack of assimilation makes coda nasals and laterals more acoustically distinct.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Most speakers of Australian languages speak with a 'pressed' voice quality, with the glottal opening narrower than in modal voice, a relatively high frequency of creaky voice, and low airflow.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] This may be due to an avoidance of breathy voice.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] This pressed quality could therefore serve to enhance the clarity of speech and ensure the perception of place of articulation distinctions.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Probably every Australian language with speakers remaining has had an orthography developed for it, in each case in the Latin script.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Sounds not found in English are usually represented by digraphs, or more rarely by diacritics, such as underlines, or extra symbols, sometimes borrowed from the International Phonetic Alphabet.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] Some examples are shown in the following table.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] In the Northern Territory, 62.5% of Aboriginal Australians spoke an indigenous language at home in 2016.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] In Queensland, almost 95% of Torres Strait Islanders spoke an indigenous language at home in 2016.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian-languages] A number of linguists and ethnographers have contributed greatly to the sum of knowledge about Australian languages.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Humans first migrated to Australia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, and over time formed as many as 500 linguistic and territorial groups.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Aboriginal people once lived across large areas of the continental shelf that were later inundated by postglacial sea-level rise at the start of the Holocene inter-glacial period, reshaping coastal landscapes and separating Tasmania from the mainland.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Aboriginal people maintained extensive networks within the continent and certain groups maintained relationships with Torres Strait Islanders and the Makassar people of modern-day Indonesia.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Over the millennia, Aboriginal people developed complex trade networks, inter-cultural relationships, law and religions, which make up some of the oldest continuous cultures in the world.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] At the time of European colonisation of Australia, the Aboriginal people spoke more than 250 different languages, possessed varying degrees of technology, and lived in various types of settlements.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Languages (or dialects) and language-associated groups of people are connected with stretches of territory known as "Country", with which they have a profound spiritual connection.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Contemporary Aboriginal beliefs are shaped by traditional beliefs, the disruption of colonisation, religions brought to the continent by later migrants, and contemporary issues.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Just over half hold secular or other spiritual beliefs or no religious affiliation; about 40% are Christian; and about 1% adhere to a traditional Aboriginal religion.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Traditional cultural beliefs are passed down and shared through dancing, stories, songlines, and art that collectively weave an ontology of modern daily life and ancient creation known as the Dreaming.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Studies of Aboriginal groups' genetic makeup are ongoing, but evidence suggests that they have genetic inheritance from ancient Asian peoples.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Aboriginal Australians and Papuans shared the same paleocontinent Sahul, although they became genetically distinct about 37,000 years ago.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Aboriginal Australians have a broadly shared, complex genetic history, but only in the last 200 years have they been defined by others as, and started to self-identify as, a single group.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Aboriginal identity has changed over time and place, with family lineage, self-identification, and community acceptance all of varying importance.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] The 2021 census shows that there were 944,171 Aboriginal people, comprising 3.7% of Australia's population.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Over 80% of Aboriginal people today speak English at home, and about 77,000 speak an Indigenous language at home.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Aboriginal people, along with Torres Strait Islander people, suffer a number of severe health and economic deprivations in comparison with the wider Australian community.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Archeological evidence indicates that the ancestors of today's Aboriginal Australians first migrated to the continent 50,000 to 65,000 years ago.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] While there have been genomic studies placing arrival as late as 43,000 years ago, a 2025 study suggests that the peopling of Australia happened around 60,000 years ago, via two distinct routes.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Early human migration to Australia was achieved when it formed a part of the Sahul continent, connected to the island of New Guinea via a land bridge.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] This would have nevertheless required crossing the sea at the Wallace Line.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] It is also possible that people came by island-hopping via an island chain between Sulawesi and New Guinea, reaching North Western Australia via Timor.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] As sea levels rose, the people on the Australian mainland and nearby islands became increasingly isolated, some on Tasmania and some of the smaller offshore islands when the land was inundated at the start of the Holocene, the inter-glacial period that started about 11,700 years ago.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] The modelling is based on data from archaeologists, anthropologists, ecologists, geneticists, climatologists, geomorphologists, and hydrologists.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] The new models suggest that the first people may have landed in the Kimberley region in what is now Western Australia about 60,000 years ago, and had settled across the continent within 6,000 years.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Aboriginal Australians may have one of the oldest continuous cultures on earth.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] In Arnhem Land in the Northern Territory, oral histories comprising complex narratives have been passed down by Yolngu people through hundreds of generations.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] The Aboriginal rock art, dated by modern techniques, shows that their culture has continued from ancient times.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Genetic studies have revealed that a population wave, termed East Eurasian Core, outgoing from the Iranian plateau during the Initial Upper Paleolithic period populated the Asia-Pacific region via a southern route dispersal.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] This wave is suggested to have expanded into the South and Southeast Asia region and subsequently diverged rapidly into the ancestors of Ancient Ancestral South Indians (AASI), Andamanese, East Asians, and Australasians, including Aboriginal Australians and Papuans.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Aboriginal Australians are genetically most closely related to other Oceanians, such as Papuans and Melanesians, who are collectively referred to as "Australasians," which can be described as "a deeply branching East Asian lineage".
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] This earlier group has been estimated to have possibly contributed around 2% ancestry to modern Aboriginal Australians.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] 2017 found the bifurcation of Eastern Eurasians and Western Eurasians dates to at least 45,000 years ago, with indigenous Australians nested inside the Eastern Eurasian clade.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Genetic data on indigenous populations of Borneo and Malaysia showed them to be more closely related to other mainland Asian groups, than compared to the groups from Papua New Guinea and Australia.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] This indicates that populations in Australia were isolated for a long time from the rest of Southeast Asia.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] They remained untouched by migrations and population expansions into that area, which can be explained by the Wallace line.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] The most common Y-chromosome haplogroups among Aboriginal Australians is C1b2, followed by haplogroups S and M; these latter haplogroups are also very frequent among Papuans.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] In a 2001 study, blood samples were collected from some Warlpiri people in the Northern Territory to study their genetic makeup (which is not representative of all Aboriginal peoples in Australia).
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] The study concluded that the Warlpiri are descended from ancient Asians whose DNA is still somewhat present in Southeastern Asian groups, although greatly diminished.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] The Warlpiri DNA lacks certain information found in modern Asian genomes, and carries information not found in other genomes.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] This reinforces the idea of ancient Aboriginal isolation.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Genetic data extracted in 2011 by Morten Rasmussen et al., who took a DNA sample from an early-20th-century lock of an Aboriginal person's hair, found that the Aboriginal ancestors probably migrated through South Asia and Maritime Southeast Asia, into Australia, where they stayed.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] As a result, outside of Africa, the Aboriginal peoples have continuously occupied the same territory longer than any other human populations.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] These findings suggest that modern Aboriginal Australians are the direct descendants of the eastern wave, who left Africa up to 75,000 years ago.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Examining DNA from a finger bone excavated in Siberia, researchers concluded that the Denisovans migrated from Siberia to tropical parts of Asia and that they interbred with modern humans in Southeast Asia 44,000 years BP, before Australia separated from New Guinea approximately 11,700 years BP.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] They contributed DNA to Aboriginal Australians and to present-day New Guineans and an indigenous tribe in the Philippines known as Mamanwa.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] This study confirms Aboriginal Australians as one of the oldest living populations in the world.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] They are possibly the oldest outside Africa, and they may have the oldest continuous culture on the planet.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] A 2016 study at the University of Cambridge suggests that it was about 50,000 years ago that these peoples reached Sahul (the supercontinent consisting of present-day Australia and its islands and New Guinea).
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] The sea levels rose and isolated Australia about 10,000 years ago, but Aboriginal Australians and Papuans diverged from each other earlier, genetically, about 37,000 years BP, possibly because the remaining land bridge was impassable.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] This isolation makes the Aboriginal people the world's oldest culture.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] The study also found evidence of an unknown hominin group, distantly related to Denisovans, with whom the Aboriginal and Papuan ancestors must have interbred, leaving a trace of about 4% in most Aboriginal Australians' genome.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] There is, however, increased genetic diversity among Aboriginal Australians based on geographical distribution.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] 2021 analysed a Holocene hunter-gatherer sample ("Leang Panninge") from South Sulawesi, which shares high amounts of genetic drift with Aboriginal Australians and Papuans.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] This suggests that a population split from the common ancestor of Aboriginal Australians and Papuans.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] The sample also shows genetic affinity with East Asians and the Andamanese people of South Asia.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] The authors note that this hunter-gatherer sample can be modelled with ~50% Australian/Papuan-related ancestry and either with ~50% East Asian or Andamanese Onge ancestry, highlighting the deep split between Leang Panninge and Aboriginal/Papuans.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] 2021 found that Philippines Negrito people split from the common ancestor of Aboriginal Australians and Papuans before the latter two diverged from each other, but after their common ancestor diverged from the ancestor of East Asian peoples.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Like Papuans, it's believed that Aboriginal Australians underwent a secondary admixture event with Altai-related Denisovan populations after they diverged from the ancestors of East Asians, who already mixed with Denisovans.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] This event was also separate from the admixture event experienced by Filipino Negritos, explaining why Aboriginal Australians and Papuans have relatively lower Denisovan ancestry.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Based on a reevaluation of mitogenomes, Gandini et al.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] 2025 proposed a "long chronology", which suggested an earlier settlement of Sahul by two migration routes about ~60 ka.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] One route came from northern Sunda via the Philippine archipelago whilst the other came from southern Sunda via Mainland Southeast Asia, with both routes ultimately tracing back to South Asia.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] The settlers that undertook these routes were ancestral to populations indigenous to Australia, New Guinea and Oceania, and were also related to other East Eurasians instead of belonging to a separate wave.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] The dingo reached Australia about 4,000 years ago.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Near that time, there were changes in language (with the Pama-Nyungan language family spreading over most of the mainland), and in stone tool technology.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] The first type of evidence comes from a 2013 study by the Max Planck Institute for Evolutionary Anthropology using large-scale genotyping data from a pool of Aboriginal Australians, New Guineans, island Southeast Asians, and Indians.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] It found that the New Guinea and Mamanwa (Philippines area) groups diverged from the Aboriginal about 36,000 years ago (there is supporting evidence that these populations are descended from migrants taking an early "southern route" out of Africa, before other groups in the area).
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Also the Indian and Australian populations mixed long before European contact, with this gene flow occurring during the Holocene (c.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] The researchers had two theories for this: either some Indians had contact with people in Indonesia who eventually transferred those Indian genes to Aboriginal Australians, or a group of Indians migrated from India to Australia and intermingled with the locals directly.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] However, a 2016 study in *Current Biology* by Anders Bergström et al. excluded the Y chromosome as providing evidence for recent gene flow from India into Australia.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] The study authors sequenced 13 Aboriginal Australian Y chromosomes using recent advances in gene sequencing technology.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] They investigated their divergence times from Y chromosomes in other continents, including comparing the haplogroup C chromosomes.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] They found a divergence time of about 54,100 years between the Sahul C chromosome and its closest relative C5, as well as about 54,300 years between haplogroups K*/M and their closest haplogroups R and Q.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] The deep divergence time of 50,000-plus years with the South Asian chromosome and "the fact that the Aboriginal Australian Cs share a more recent common ancestor with Papuan Cs" excludes any recent genetic contact.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] They attributed the disparity between their results and previous findings to improvements in technology; none of the other studies had utilised complete Y chromosome sequencing, which has the highest precision.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] For example, use of a ten Y STRs method has been shown to massively underestimate divergence times.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Bergström's 2018 doctoral thesis looking at the population of Sahul suggests that other than relatively recent admixture, the populations of the region appear to have been genetically independent from the rest of the world since their divergence about 50,000 years ago.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] He writes "There is no evidence for South Asian gene flow to Australia ....
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Aboriginal Australians possess inherited abilities to adapt to a wide range of environmental temperatures in various ways.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] A study in 1958 comparing cold adaptation in the desert-dwelling Pitjantjatjara people compared with a group of European people showed that the cooling adaptation of the Aboriginal group differed from that of the Europeans, and that they were able to sleep more soundly through a cold desert night.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] A 2014 Cambridge University study found that a beneficial mutation in two genes that regulate thyroxine, a hormone involved in regulating body metabolism, helps to regulate body temperature in response to fever.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] The effect of this is that the desert people are able to have a higher body temperature without accelerating the activity of the whole of the body, which can be especially detrimental in childhood diseases.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] This helps protect people to survive the side-effects of infection.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] It is estimated that the Indigenous Australian population at the time of first European settlement numbered at least 314,500 people.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Based on the 2021 census, the Australian Bureau of Statistics estimates there were 901,655 Aboriginal Australians, and 42,516 who identified as both Aboriginal Australian and Torres Strait Islander.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] These groups comprise 3.7% of the total Australian population.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] 39,538 people identified as Torres Strait Islander, which is a different ethnic group from Aboriginal Australian.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Based on initial 2021 census counts, the Aboriginal and Torres Strait islander population grew 25.2%, since the previous census in 2016.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Demographic factors – births, deaths and migration – accounted for 43.5% of the increase (71,086 people).
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] In turn, 76.2% of that increase was attributed to people aged 0–19 years in 2021, broken down as 52.5% for 0–4 year olds (births since 2016) and 23.7% for 5–19 year olds.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Reasons for the increase in Aboriginal population also include non-demographic factors.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] These include changes in individuals' identification as Aboriginal or Torres Strait Islander in different censuses, and individuals completing a census form in 2021 but not in 2016.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] These factors accounted for 56.5% of the increase in the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander population.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Indigenous Australians (including Torres Strait Islanders) are less likely to live in the major Australian cities than are non-Indigenous Australians (41% compared with 73%).
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Although humans arrived in Australia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, it is possible that the ancestor language of existing Aboriginal languages is as recent as 12,000 years old.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Over 250 Australian Aboriginal languages are thought to have existed at the time of first European contact.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] As of 2021, 84% of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islanders spoke only English at home.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] The National Indigenous Languages Survey (NILS) for 2018-19 found that more than 120 Indigenous language varieties were in use or being revived, although 70 of those in use are endangered.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] The 2021 census found that 167 Indigenous languages were spoken at home by 76,978 Indigenous Australians.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] NILS and the Australian Bureau of Statistics use different classifications for Indigenous Australian languages.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] According to the 2021 census, the classifiable Aboriginal languages with the most speakers are Kriol (7,403), Djambarrpuyngu (3,839), Pitjantjatjara (3,399), Warlpiri (2,592), Murrinh Patha (2,063) and Tiwi (2,053).
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] There were also over 10,000 people who spoke an Indigenous language that could not be further defined or classified.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] A number of English-based creoles have arisen in Australia after European contact, of which Kriol is among the strongest and fastest-growing Aboriginal languages.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Kriol is spoken in the Northern Territory and Western Australia.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] It is estimated that there are 20,000 to 30,000 speakers of Indigenous creole languages.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Before British colonisation, there were perhaps five to sixteen languages on Tasmania, possibly related to one another in four language families.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] The last speaker of a traditional Tasmanian language, Fanny Cochrane Smith, died in 1905.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Palawa kani is an in-progress constructed language, built from a composite of surviving words from various Tasmanian Aboriginal languages.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Traditional Indigenous languages often incorporated sign systems to aid communication with the hearing impaired, to complement verbal communication, and to replace verbal communication when the spoken language was forbidden for cultural reasons.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Many of these sign systems are still in use.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Dispersing across the Australian continent over time, the ancient people expanded and differentiated into distinct groups, each with its own language and culture.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] More than 400 distinct Australian Aboriginal peoples have been identified, distinguished by names designating their ancestral languages, dialects, or distinctive speech patterns.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] According to noted anthropologist, archaeologist and sociologist Harry Lourandos, historically, these groups lived in three main cultural areas, the Northern, Southern and Central cultural areas.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] The Northern and Southern areas, having richer natural marine and woodland resources, were more densely populated than the Central area.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Other group names are based on the language group or specific dialect spoken.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] These also coincide with geographical regions of varying sizes.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] However, these lists are neither exhaustive nor definitive, and there are overlaps.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Different approaches have been taken by non-Aboriginal scholars in trying to understand and define Aboriginal culture and societies, some focusing on the micro-level (tribe, clan, etc.), and others on shared languages and cultural practices spread over large regions defined by ecological factors.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Anthropologists have encountered many difficulties in trying to define what constitutes an Aboriginal people/community/group/tribe, let alone naming them.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Knowledge of pre-colonial Aboriginal cultures and societal groupings is still largely dependent on the observers' interpretations, which were filtered through colonial ways of viewing societies.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Some Aboriginal peoples identify as one of several saltwater, freshwater, rainforest or desert peoples.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] The term *Aboriginal Australians* includes many distinct peoples who have developed across Australia for over 50,000 years.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] These peoples have a broadly shared, complex, genetic history, but it is only in the last two hundred years that they have been defined and have started to self-identify as a single group socio-politically.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] While some preferred the term *Aborigine* to *Aboriginal* in the past, as the latter was seen to have more directly discriminatory legal origins, use of the term *Aborigine* has declined in recent decades, as many consider the term an offensive and racist hangover from Australia's colonial era.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] The definition of the term *Aboriginal* has changed over time and place, with family lineage, self-identification and community acceptance all being of varying importance.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] The term *Indigenous Australians* refers to Aboriginal Australians and Torres Strait Islander peoples, and the term is conventionally only used when both groups are included in the topic being addressed, or by self-identification by a person as Indigenous.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] As of 2021, 51% of Indigenous people stated that they held a secular or other spiritual belief or no religious affiliation; 41% were affiliated to Christianity; and 1% were affiliated to a traditional Aboriginal religion.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Australian Indigenous people have beliefs unique to each mob (tribe) and have a strong connection to the land.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Contemporary Indigenous Australian beliefs are a complex mixture, varying by region and individual across the continent.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] They are shaped by traditional beliefs, the disruption of colonisation, religions brought to the continent by Europeans, and contemporary issues.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Traditional cultural beliefs are passed down and shared by dancing, stories, songlines and art—especially Papunya Tula (dot painting)—collectively telling the story of creation known as The Dreamtime.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Additionally, traditional healers were also custodians of important Dreaming stories as well as their medical roles (for example the Ngangkari in the Western desert).
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Some core structures and themes are shared across the continent with details and additional elements varying between language and cultural groups.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] For example, in The Dreamtime of most regions, a spirit creates the earth then tells the humans to treat the animals and the earth in a way that is respectful to land.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] In Northern Territory this spirit is commonly said to be a huge snake or snakes that weaved its way through the earth and sky making the mountains and oceans.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] But in other places the spirits who created the world are known as wandjina rain and water spirits.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Major ancestral spirits include the Rainbow Serpent, Baiame, Dirawong and Bunjil.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Similarly, the Arrernte people of central Australia believed that humanity originated from great superhuman ancestors who brought the sun, wind and rain as a result of breaking through the surface of the Earth when waking from their slumber.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Many Dreamtime stories are still believed by many Indigenous Australians to this day.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Taken as a whole, Aboriginal Australians, along with Torres Strait Islander people, have a number of health and economic deprivations in comparison with the wider Australian community.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Due to the aforementioned disadvantage, Aboriginal Australian communities experience a higher rate of suicide, as compared to non-indigenous communities.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] These issues stem from a variety of different causes unique to indigenous communities, such as historical trauma, socioeconomic disadvantage, and decreased access to education and health care.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Also, this problem largely affects indigenous youth, as many indigenous youth may feel disconnected from their culture.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] To combat the increased suicide rate, many researchers have suggested that the inclusion of more cultural aspects into suicide prevention programs would help to combat mental health issues within the community.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Past studies have found that many indigenous leaders and community members, do in fact, want more culturally-aware health care programs.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Similarly, culturally-relative programs targeting indigenous youth have actively challenged suicide ideation among younger indigenous populations, with many social and emotional wellbeing programs using cultural information to provide coping mechanisms and improving mental health.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] Indigenous communities in remote Australia are often small, isolated towns with basic facilities, on traditionally owned land.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] These communities have between 20 and 300 inhabitants and are often closed to outsiders for cultural reasons.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-australian] The long-term viability and resilience of Aboriginal communities in desert areas has been discussed by scholars and policy-makers.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-corporation] The corporation nominated hold and manage (as trustee) or manage (as agent) before native title determination and registration, is called a **Prescribed Body Corporate** (**PBC**).
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-corporation] In 2015, there were 144 RNTBCs registered with the Office of the Registrar of Indigenous Corporations (ORIC).
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-corporation] PBCs are required to register with ORIC, under the provisions of the *Native Title Act 1993*.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-corporation] They must have the words "registered native title body corporate" or "RNTBC" in their name, while other Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander corporations can choose to register under other state or territory associations law, or under the *Corporations Act 2001* (Cth).
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-corporation] A Registered Native Title Body Corporate represents an Indigenous Australian group's native title rights and interests, after these have been recognised by the Federal Court and the body is registered.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-corporation] Before the court determination and registration of the body, it is known as a Prescribed Body Corporate.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-corporation] It is at this point that their statutory obligations under the *NTA* and the *Native Title (Prescribed Bodies Corporate) Regulations 1999* are triggered.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-corporation] PBCs have prescribed characteristics under the *Native Title Act 1993* (*NTA*), including that they are incorporated under the *Corporations (Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander) Act 2006* ("*CATSI Act*").
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-corporation] In some instances, native title claim groups will create a new organisation whose sole purpose is to act as an RNTBC.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-corporation] Alternatively, they may nominate an existing corporation to become the RNTBC as long as it is already incorporated under the *CATSI Act* and complies with the provisions of the NTA.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-corporation] Importantly, it must have, among its purposes, the purpose of becoming an RNTBC.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-corporation] The kind of bodies that can be determined as PBCs (and therefore registered as RNTBCs) and their functions are set out in the *Native Title Act 1993* and *Native Title (Prescribed Bodies Corporate) Regulations 1999*.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-corporation] As of 2015, there were 144 RNTBCs registered with ORIC, compared with 9 in 2000.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-corporation] There are many more native title claims than RNTBCs, as the same RNTBC may undertake any number of claims.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-corporation] There directors of the corporations were about 56.1 percent male and 43.9 percent female, and 29 RNTBCs appeared in the top 500 corporations in the 2014–15 financial year.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-corporation] Some Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander corporations are not RNTBCs (often referred to as "native title corporations" or "traditional owner corporations"), but may have generated native title outcomes without having a native title determination.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-corporation] There is a network of native title representative bodies (NTRBs) and native title service providers (NTSPs) to assist native title claimants and holders, of which the National Indigenous Australians Agency (NIAA) funds 14.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] In Australia, **Indigenous land rights** or **Aboriginal land rights** are the rights and interests in land of Aboriginal Australians and Torres Strait Islander people; the term may also include the struggle for those rights.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] As of 2020, Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples’ rights and interests in land are formally recognised over around 40 per cent of Australia’s land mass, and sea rights have also been asserted in various native title cases.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] Native title in Australia includes rights and interests relating to land and waters held by Indigenous Australians under traditional laws and customs, and recognised in accordance with the *Native Title Act 1993* (Cth).
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] Although this is federal legislation and therefore applicable to the whole of Australia, the way in which the processes for native title operate in each state and territory is dependent on the history of the land rights arrangements of the particular state or territory.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] In some jurisdictions, titles to large areas of traditional lands were granted before the Act commenced.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] The *Native Title Act* was passed following the High Court of Australia decision of *Mabo v Queensland* (No.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] 2), which recognised for the first time that Indigenous people had rights to land sourced from their continuing connection to it and that these rights are recognised under Australian common law.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] Where these rights had not been extinguished through contradictory Crown grants, native titles continued to exist and could exist alongside certain title, such as crown leases.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] Different types of land rights laws exist in Australia, allowing for the renewed ownership of land to Indigenous Australians under various conditions.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] Land rights schemes are in place in the Northern Territory, Queensland (including the Torres Strait Islands), New South Wales, South Australia, Victoria and Tasmania.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] The land titles may recognise traditional interest in the land and protect those interests by giving Aboriginal people legal ownership of that land.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] Also, according to the National Native Title Tribunal: "A successful land rights claim usually results in a special grant of freehold title or perpetual lease.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] A title document for the land is issued.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] The title is normally held by a community or an organisation, not by individuals.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] There are usually some restrictions on selling, and dealing with, land that has been granted in a land rights claim.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] Normally, the land will be passed down to future generations in a way that recognises the community’s traditional connection to that country".
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] Indigenous land rights relate to the rights and interests in land of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people in Australia, and the term is also used to describe the struggle for those rights.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] As of 2020, Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples’ rights and interests in land are formally recognised over around 40 per cent of Australia’s land mass.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] The recognition of Indigenous rights in land and waters is fundamental to the process of reconciliation.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] The colonisation of mainland Australia started in the 1700s, while the Torres Strait Islands were only taken over by the colony of Queensland in the 1870s.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] During the late 19th and early 20th centuries, the movement of Aboriginal peoples in Australia was controlled by colony- and later state-based laws, such as the *Aboriginals Protection and Restriction of the Sale of Opium Act 1897* in Queensland.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] This often meant that they were confined to living on Aboriginal reserves or mission stations, where they had no rights to land ownership.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] The passing of Aboriginal land rights legislation in Australia in the late 20th century was preceded by a number of important Aboriginal protests.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] The modern land rights movement started with the 1963 Yolngu Bark Petition, when Yolngu people from the remote settlement of Yirrkala, in north-east Arnhem Land, petitioned the federal government to have their land and rights given back.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] The 1966 Wave Hill Walk-Off, or Gurundji Strike, started with a protest about working conditions, but grew into a lands right issue, with the people claiming rights to the land which was then a cattle station owned by a large British company, Vesteys.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] In 1961, at the Native Welfare Conference, a meeting of federal and state ministers responsible for Aboriginal welfare, agreed on a policy of assimilation.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] The measures included the removal of discriminatory legislation and restrictive practices, welfare measures, education and training to assist the involvement of Aboriginal people in the economy, and the education of non-Indigenous Australians about Aboriginal culture and history.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] It brought about a more widespread awareness by non-Indigenous people to social justice for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] South Australian premier Sir Thomas Playford argued for integration rather than assimilation of Aboriginal people, and others questioned the concept of assimilation, with its paternalistic attitude.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] The *Aboriginal Lands Trust Act 1966* (SA) established the South Australian Aboriginal Lands Trust (ALT).
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] This was the first major recognition of Aboriginal land rights by any Australian government, and predated the 1967 Referendum.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] It allowed for parcels of Aboriginal land previously held by the SA Government, to be handed to the Aboriginal Lands Trust of SA under the Act.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] The Trust was governed by a Board composed solely of Aboriginal people.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] In the 1970s, Indigenous Australians became more politically active, and a powerful movement for the recognition of Indigenous land rights emerged.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] Also during this decade, the federal government started buying privately owned land in order to benefit Indigenous communities, and also to create Crown land which would be available for claim.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] In 1971, Justice Richard Blackburn of the Supreme Court of the Northern Territory ruled against the Yolngu in *Milirrpum v Nabalco Pty Ltd* (the "Gove land rights case"), when they sought native title rights over the Gove Peninsula.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] However, Justice Blackburn did acknowledge the claimants' ritual and economic use of the land and that they had an established system of law "a subtle and highly elaborate" system of laws (*Madayin*).
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] In this way, this was the first significant legal case for Aboriginal land rights in Australia.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] The Aboriginal Tent Embassy was set up on the front lawns of Old Parliament House, Canberra on 26 January (Australia Day) 1972, by four Aboriginal activists, Michael Anderson, Billy Craigie, Tony Coorey and Bertie Williams (later Kevin "Bert" Johnson, as protest for Indigenous land rights.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] The Black Moratorium refers to protests which took place on 14 July 1972.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] The Sydney protest was in the form of marches from Redfern, Sydney University and other points, to Sydney Town Hall, attended by around 6,000 protesters, who included Aboriginal people, students and trade unionists.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] Gary Foley printed a pamphlet at Sydney University ahead of the protest.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] Unionists from several trades, including builders' labourers, ship painters, dockers and teachers, had voted to go on strike for half a day in support of Aboriginal people, and around 2,000 students joined the protest.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] There were also protests in Newcastle, Brisbane, and Darwin, all under the rallying cry of "Ningla-A-na" (Arrernte for "hungry land").
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] The moratorium as a tactic was copied from the campaign against the Vietnam War: a weekday protest meant that union supporters would need to convince others in their workplace about why solidarity with Aboriginal people was an important issue for their movement.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] Striking would both disrupt the economy and show strong conviction and understanding of the struggle, and the discussion put Black rights into workplaces, staff rooms and classrooms.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] It was later assessed as one of the most successful and historically significant protests for Aboriginal rights in Australia until this time.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] Its legacy included the establishments of networks which led to thousands of people defending the Tent Embassy against attempts by police to shut it down, and union funding helped keep the embassy running.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] The Moratorium showed that non-Indigenous workers could be strong allies in the struggle for Indigenous rights.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] Bruce McGuinness published an article in the November issue of *Aboriginal and Islander Identity* magazine about the march in Melbourne, which was attended by about 2000 people, including an estimated 16% of the Black population.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] In the wake of *Milirrpum*, the Aboriginal Land Rights Commission (also known as the "Woodward Royal Commission") was established in the Northern Territory in 1973.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] This Royal Commission, chaired by Justice Woodward, made a number of recommendations in favour of recognising Aboriginal Land Rights.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] Taking up many of these recommendations, the Whitlam government introduced an Aboriginal Land Rights Bill to Parliament; however, this lapsed upon the dismissal of the government in 1975.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] The succeeding conservative government, led by Malcolm Fraser, reintroduced a Bill, though not of the same content, and it was signed by the governor-general of Australia on 16 December 1976.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] The *Aboriginal Land Rights Act 1976* established the basis upon which Aboriginal people in the Northern Territory could claim rights to land based on traditional occupation.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] The statute, the first of the Aboriginal land rights acts, was significant in that it allowed a claim of title if claimants could provide evidence of their traditional association with land.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] Four Land Councils were established in the Northern Territory under this law.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] The *Aboriginal Land Rights Act 1976* established a procedure that transferred almost 50 per cent of land in the Northern Territory (around 600 000 km2) to collective Aboriginal ownership.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] Following this, some states introduced their own land rights legislation; however, there were significant limitations on the returned lands, or that available for claim.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] Paul Coe, in *Coe v Commonwealth* (1979), attempted (unsuccessfully) to bring a class action on behalf of all "Aborigines" claiming all of Australia.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] In 1981 South Australian premier David Tonkin returned 102,650 square kilometres (39,630 sq mi) of land (10.2% of the state's land area) to the Pitjantjara/Yankunytjatjara people, as the APY lands.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] The land rights legislation was introduced by Premier Don Dunstan in November 1978, several months prior to his resignation from Parliament.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] An amended bill, following extensive consultation, was passed by the Tonkin Liberal Government, as the *Anangu Pitjantjatjara Yankunytjatjara Land Rights Act 1981*.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] In 1984 Premier John Bannon's Labor Government passed the *Maralinga Tjarutja Land Rights Act 1984* to return lands to the Pitjantjara people in the remote western area of the state.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] The legislation was proclaimed in January 1985 and was followed by a ceremony in the desert attended by Maralinga Tjarutja leader Archie Barton, John Bannon and Aboriginal Affairs Minister Greg Crafter.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] In February 2019, the ILC became the Indigenous Land and Sea Corporation (ILSC), in recognition of its operations on water.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] The ILSC is funded by an annual payment from the investment returns of the Australian Government's Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Land Account.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] The *Aboriginal Land Rights (Northern Territory) Act 1976* (see above) provides the basis upon which Aboriginal Australian people in the Northern Territory can claim rights to land based on traditional occupation.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] The freehold land cannot be sold or transferred, but it can be leased.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] In 2025, the High Court of Australia upheld an earlier ruling from the Federal Court in an action brought by Yunupingu on behalf of the Gumatj peoples of the Northern Territory.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] The decision potentially means the Commonwealth may be liable to claims of compensation for decisions made which extinguished native title claims for territories under its administration.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] The Northern Territory was under the administration of the Commonwealth from its creation in 1911 to 1978 when it was granted self-government.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] In Queensland, the *Aboriginal Land Act 1991* and the *Torres Strait Islander Land Act 1991* provide for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander freehold respectively.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander freehold land occupies 5%, or 59,489 square kilometres (22,969 sq mi) of northern Queensland.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] A Registered Native Title Body Corporate (RNTBC) can be trustee of this land, who can grant leases of up to 99 years for any purpose.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] A third type of land tenure, mainly held by Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander communities in remote and regional Queensland, is the Deed of Grant in Trust (DOGIT).
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] These were established primarily to administer former Aboriginal reserves and missions.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] They came about through legislation passed by the Queensland Government in 1984.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander local governments hold trusteeship of the DOGITs, and land tenure under this type of tenure is held in collective title, held in trust for future generations.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] From 1 January 2015, some trustees, namely those classified as "urban" or "future urban") are able to convert parts of the collective title to either Aboriginal freehold or Torres Strait Islander freehold title.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] Mer (Murray) Island (the subject of the Mabo No.1 (1988) and No.2 (1992) cases) is Torres Strait Islander freehold and Aurukun is Aboriginal freehold land.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] In the 2013 Review of the *Aboriginal Lands Trust Act 1966*, the powers of the Trust were reviewed and changed to modernise the Trust and the *Aboriginal Lands Trust of South Australia Act 2013* (SA) was passed.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] The Aboriginal Lands Trust (ALT) of Western Australia was established by the *Aboriginal Affairs Planning Authority Act 1972*.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] There are different types of tenures held by different parts of this land, including reserves, leases and freehold property.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] There are many remote communities on this land, inhabited by about 12,000 people.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] Land reform is ongoing, to use the land in a way which benefits the Aboriginal people.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] Since the 2010s, there has been a growing number of freemen on the land / sovereign citizen groups targeting Indigenous Australians, with groups with names like Tribal Sovereign Parliament of Gondwana Land, the Original Sovereign Tribal Federation (OSTF) and the Original Sovereign Confederation.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] OSTF Founder Mark McMurtrie, an Aboriginal Australian man, has produced YouTube videos speaking about “common law”, which incorporate Freemen beliefs.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] Appealing to other Aboriginal people by partly identifying with the land rights movement, McMurtrie played on their feelings of alienation and lack of trust in the systems which had not served Indigenous people well.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-land-rights-in-australia] Proponents of the original ideas are often related to far-right movements, whose core beliefs may be broadly defined as "see[ing] the state as a corporation with no authority over free citizens".
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] Protectors of Aborigines were appointed by the Board under the conditions laid down in the various Acts.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] In theory, protectors of Aborigines were often empowered to undertake legal proceedings on behalf of Aboriginal people, dictate where Aboriginal people could live or work, and keep all wages earned by employed Aboriginals.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] The exact powers varied over time and by jurisdiction.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] As the boards had limited funds, protectors received very limited remuneration.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] A range of people were appointed as local protectors, including resident magistrates, jail wardens, justices of the peace and, in some cases ministers of religion, though most were local police inspectors.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] The minutes of the boards show they mostly dealt with matters of requests from religious bodies for financial relief and reports from resident or police magistrates pertaining to trials and convictions of Aboriginal people under their jurisdiction.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] Aboriginal protection boards also issued permits to allow Aboriginal people the right to leave their respective missions and reserves and enter the mainstream society for a set period of time.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] The *Central Board Appointed to Watch Over the Interests of the Aborigines* was established in 1860.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] This was replaced by the *Victorian Central Board for the Protection of Aborigines* in 1869 (via the *Aboriginal Protection Act 1869),* making Victoria the first colony to enact comprehensive regulations on the lives of Aboriginal Victorians.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] The board exerted an extraordinary level of control over people's lives including regulation of residence, slavery as employment, marriage, social life and other aspects of daily life.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] The Victorian Half-Caste Act of 1886 gave the Board extensive new powers over the lives of Aboriginal people, including regulation of residence, employment and marriage.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] In particular, the 1886 Act started to remove Aboriginal people of mixed descent, known as "half-castes", from Aboriginal stations or reserves to force them to assimilate into European society.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] These expulsions separated families and communities, causing distress and leading to protest.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] Nevertheless, the board refused to assist the expelled people.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] It was assumed that the expulsions would lead to the decline in the population of the reserves and their eventual closure.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] The *Aborigines Act 1910* increased the rights of Aboriginal people in Victoria.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] The board was abolished in 1957 by the *Aborigines Act 1957*.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] The *Aboriginal Lands Act 1970* gave recognition of Aboriginal people's right to land.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] Under this Act the deeds of land at the Lake Tyers Mission and Framlingham reserves were transferred to the communities.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] The New South Wales Board for the Protection of Aborigines was established in 1883 and was reconstituted under the *Aborigines Protection Act 1909* with wide-ranging control over the lives of Aboriginal people.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] The Board also controlled their freedom of movement and personal finances.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] In particular, Aboriginal children could be removed from their homes and families and taken into care to be raised like white children, becoming the Stolen Generations.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] The 1911 amendment to the *Aboriginal Protection Act* established the Kinchela Aboriginal Boys' Training Home and the Cootamundra Domestic Training Home for Aboriginal Girls.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] Aboriginal children were removed from their families for various welfare reasons and transported to Kinchela and Cootamundra, where they were often abused and neglected while being taught farm labouring and domestic work, many of them ending up as servants in the homes of wealthy Sydney residents.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] The Board was renamed the Aborigines Welfare Board (which was frequently referred to as the Aborigin**al** Welfare Board in later sources) in 1940 by the *Aborigines Protection (Amendment) Act 1940*, which stipulated that Aboriginal people should be assimilated into mainstream white society.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] It intended that Aboriginal culture would evaporate, and Aboriginal people would eventually become indistinguishable from Europeans.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] The Board consisted of 11 members, including two Aboriginal people, one "full-blood" and one having "a mixture of Aboriginal blood".
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] It was abolished under the *Aborigines Act 1969* (NSW).
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] After its abolition, the NSW Aboriginal Advisory Council was formed, which advised the NSW Minister for Aboriginal Affairs directly.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] The Western Australian Aborigines Protection Board operated between 1 January 1886 and 1 April 1898 as a statutory authority.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] It was created by the *Aborigines Protection Act 1886* (50 Vict.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] 25 (WA)), also known as the *Half-Caste Act*, described as *An Act to provide for the better protection and management of the Aboriginal Natives of Western Australia, and to amend the Law relating to certain Contracts with such Aboriginal Natives*, and the *Aborigines Act 1889* (52 Vict.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] The 1886 act was enacted following the furore over the Fairburn Report (which revealed slavery conditions among Aboriginal farm workers) and the work of the Rev.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] The act introduced employment contracts between employers and Aboriginal workers over the age of 14.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] There was no provision in the 1886 act for contracts to include wages, but employees were to be provided with "substantial, good and sufficient rations", clothing and blankets.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] The 1886 act provided a resident magistrate with the power to indenture 'half-caste' and Aboriginal children, from a suitable age, until they turned 21.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] An Aboriginal Protection Board was also established to prevent the abuses reported earlier, but rather than protect Aborigines, it mainly succeeded in putting them under tighter government control.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] It was intended to enforce contracts, employment of prisoners and apprenticeships, but there was not sufficient power to enforce clauses in the north, and they were openly flouted.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] The act defined as "Aboriginal" as "every Aboriginal native of Australia, every Aboriginal half-caste, or child of a half-caste".
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] Governor Broome insisted that the act contain within it a clause permitting traditional owners to continue hunting on their tribal lands.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] The effect of the act was to give increasing power to the board over Aboriginal people, rather than setting up a system to punish whites for wrongdoing in relation to Aboriginal people.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] An Aboriginal Department was set up, under the office of the Chief Protector of Aborigines.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] Nearly half of the Legislative Council voted to amend the act for contract labour as low as age 10 but it was defeated.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] McKenzie Grant, the member for The North, claimed that child labour of age six or seven was a necessary commonplace, as "in this way they gradually become domesticated".
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] The attorney general Septimus Burt, in debate on the 2nd reading speech, claimed that contracts were being issued, not for current work, but to hold Aboriginal people as slaves on stations for potential future work, and so prevent them from being free to leave.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] In 1898, the board was replaced by the Aborigines Department.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] The Queensland Aboriginal Protection Board was established by the *Aboriginals Protection and Restriction of the Sale of Opium Act 1897*.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] The *Aborigines Act Amendment Act 1939* created the Aborigines Protection Board in South Australia, which was "charged with the duty of controlling and promoting the welfare" of Aboriginal people (which included anyone descended from an Aboriginal person).
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] Charles Duguid was a founding board member; other board members included J.
[src:arnhem-land/aboriginal-protection-board] By the late 1960s, all states and territories had repealed the legislation allowing for the removal of Aboriginal children under the policy of 'protection'.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] Two regions are often distinguished as **East Arnhem** (**Land**) and **West Arnhem** (**Land**).
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] The region's service hub is Nhulunbuy, 600 km (370 mi) east of Darwin, set up in the early 1970s as a mining town for bauxite.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] Other major population centres are Yirrkala (just outside Nhulunbuy), Gunbalanya (formerly Oenpelli), Ramingining, and Maningrida.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] A substantial proportion of the population, who are mostly Aboriginal, live on small outstations or homelands.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] This outstation movement started in the early 1980s.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] Many Aboriginal groups moved to usually very small settlements on their traditional lands, often to escape the problems of the larger towns.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] These population groups have very little Western cultural influence, and Arnhem Land is arguably one of the last areas in Australia that could be seen as a completely separate country.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] Many of the region's leaders have called and continue to call for a treaty that would allow the Yolŋu people to operate under their own traditional laws.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] In 2013–14, the entire region contributed around A$1.3 billion or 7 percent to the Northern Territory's gross state product, mainly through bauxite mining.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] In 2019, it was announced that NASA had chosen Arnhem Land as the location for a space launch facility, the Arnhem Space Centre.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] On 27 June 2022, NASA launched the first rocket there, the first rocket launch from a commercial spaceport outside the US, and two further launches followed within weeks.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] The Yolŋu culture in East Arnhem Land is possibly one of the oldest living cultures on Earth; humans are known to have inhabited the region for about 60,000 years.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] DNA studies have confirmed that "Aboriginal Australians are one of the oldest living populations in the world, certainly the oldest outside of Africa"; their descendants left the African continent 75,000 years ago.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] They may have the oldest continuous culture on earth.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] Oral histories comprising complex narratives have been passed down through hundreds of generations, and the Aboriginal rock art, dated by modern techniques, shows continuity of their culture.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] Arnhem Land is the location of the oldest-known (as of 2010) stone axe of its kind, which scholars believe to be 35,500 years old.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] Rock art depicting what may be acts of violence between people in Arnhem Land has been tentatively dated to 10,000 years ago.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] At least since the 18th century (and probably earlier) Muslim traders from Makassar of Sulawesi visited Arnhem Land each year to trade, harvest, and process sea cucumbers or *trepang*.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] This marine animal is highly prized in Chinese cuisine, for folk medicine, and as an aphrodisiac.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] This Makassan contact with Australia is the first recorded example of interaction between the inhabitants of the Australian continent and their Asian neighbours.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] The Makassan name for Arnhem land or the northern Australian coast is *Marege'*, meaning "wild country".
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] This contact had a major effect on local Aboriginal Australians.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] The Makassans exchanged goods such as cloth, tobacco, knives, rice, and alcohol for the right to *trepang* coastal waters and employ local labour.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] Makassar pidgin became a *lingua franca* along the north coast among several indigenous Australian groups who were brought into greater contact with each other by the seafaring Makassan culture.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] These traders from the southwest corner of Sulawesi also introduced the word *balanda* for white people, long before western explorers set foot on the coasts of northern Australia.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] In Arnhem Land, the word is still widely used today to refer to white Australians.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] The Dutch started settling in Sulawesi Island in the early 17th century.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] Archaeological remains of Makassar contact, including trepang processing plants (drying, smoking) from the 18th and 19th centuries, are still found at Australian locations such as Port Essington and Groote Eylandt.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] The Makassans also planted tamarind trees (native to Madagascar and East Africa).
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] After processing, the sea cucumbers were traded by the Makassans to Southern China.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] In 2014, an 18th-century Chinese coin was found in the remote area of Wessel Islands off the coast on a beach on Elcho Island during a historical expedition.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] The coin was found near previously known Makassan trepanger fishing sites where several other Dutch coins have been discovered nearby, but never a Chinese coin.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] The coin was probably made in Beijing around 1735.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] In 1884, 10,000 square miles of Arnhem Land was sold by the colonial British government to cattle grazier John Arthur Macartney.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] The property was called Florida Station and Macartney stocked it with cattle overlanded from Queensland.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] Monsoonal flooding, disease and strong resistance from the local Aboriginal population resulted in Florida Station being abandoned by Macartney in 1893.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] The first manager of the property, Jim Randell, bolted a swivel cannon to the verandah of the homestead to keep the Indigenous people away, while Jack Watson, the last manager of the property, reportedly "wiped out a lot" of "the blacks" living on the coast at Blue Mud Bay.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] During the period of Watson's management, another large massacre is recorded to have happened at Mirki on the north coast of Florida Station.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] The Yolngu people today remember this massacre where many people including children were shot dead.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] From 1903 to 1908, the property rights of much of Arnhem Land were held by the Eastern and African Cold Storage Supply Company.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] This Anglo-Australian consortium leased the region under the name of Arafura cattle station and attempted to construct a massive cattle raising and meat production industry.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] The company employed roving gangs of armed men to shoot the resident Aboriginal population.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] After exploration for bauxite commenced near Yirrkala mission on the Gove Peninsula without consulting the local people, the Yirrkala bark petitions were created and presented to federal parliament in 1963.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] In 1971, the Gove land rights case (*Milirrpum v Nabalco Pty Ltd*) was the first litigation on native title in Australia, and the first significant legal case for Aboriginal land rights in Australia.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] The ruling was upheld by the High Court on 12 March 2025, where parties are entitled to a fair compensation of at most AUD700 million.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] The area is from Port Roper on the Gulf of Carpentaria around the coast to the East Alligator River, where it adjoins Kakadu National Park.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] The major centres are Jabiru on the Kakadu National Park border, Maningrida at the Liverpool River mouth, and Nhulunbuy (also known as Gove) in the far north-east, on the Gove Peninsula.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] Gove is the site of large-scale bauxite mining with an associated alumina refinery.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] Its administrative centre is the town of Nhulunbuy, the fourth-largest population centre in the Northern Territory.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] The climate of Arnhem Land is tropical monsoon with a wet and dry season.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] The temperature has little seasonal variation; however, it can range from overnight lows of 15 °C (59 °F) in the dry season (April to September) to daily highs of 33 °C (91 °F) in the wet season (October to March).
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] Various Aboriginal peoples lived across the continent before the colonisation of Australia, including various tribes across the Northern Territory before its colonisation.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] Yolngu peoples lived in Arnhem Land for centuries, first encountering outsiders when they traded with Macassans.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] In 1931, an area of 96,000 km2 (37,000 sq mi) was proclaimed as an Aboriginal reserve, named Arnhem Land Aboriginal Reserve.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] As of 2007 the Land Trust held about 100,000 km2 (39,000 sq mi) as Aboriginal freehold land (with the exception of mining leases).
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] Arnhem Land is composed of many different Aboriginal countries and language groups.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] North-east Arnhem Land is home to the Yolngu people, one of the largest Indigenous groups in Australia, who have succeeded in maintaining a vigorous traditional culture, and whose name for this area is Miwatj.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] The term *Yolngu* simply means "person", but has come to mean the group of intermarrying clans who live in this part of Arnhem Land, and whose members speak mainly one of many Yolŋu languages, or Yolngu Matha.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] The North East Arnhem Land Aboriginal Corporation (NEAL) is made up of 26 elder-leaders (*dilak*), representing the 26 clans (*bäpurru*) of North East Arnhem Land who have sovereignty over certain areas of land and waters.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] Kinship ties, territorial claims, and other social issues are managed by the clan system.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] In West Arnhem Land, large groups include the Bininj people and the Maung people of the Goulburn Islands.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] There are three electoral districts within Arnhem land for the purpose of electing members of the Northern Territory Government.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] For federal government, Arnhem Land lies within the Division of Lingiari.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] East Arnhem Regional Council services six remote communities in East Arnhem Land: Galiwin'ku (Elcho Island), Gapuwiyak, Ramingining, Yirrkala, Milingimbi Island, and Gunyangara.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] In the 2021 census, 6,281 people were living in West Arnhem, of whom around 81 per cent are Aboriginal.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] The West Arnhem Regional Council covers an area of just under 50,000 km2 (19,000 sq mi), which includes five remote communities or wards: Jabiru, Gunbalanya, Maningrida, Warruwi (on South Goulburn Island), and Minjilang, as well as two islands and over 100 homelands.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] In 2013–14, the entire region contributed around A$1.3 billion or 7% to the Northern Territory's gross state product, mainly through bauxite mining.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] In 2019, it was announced that NASA had chosen Arnhem Land as the location for a space launch facility.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] The Arnhem Space Centre was built near Nhulunbuy, employing mostly local labour, and on 27 June 2022, NASA launched the first rocket there, which was the first rocket launch from a commercial spaceport outside the US.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] Two further launches followed, the third on 11 July.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] The 2006 film *Ten Canoes* captures life in Arnhem Land through a story tapping into the Aboriginal mythic past; it was co-directed by one of the indigenous cast members.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] The Aboriginal community of Yirrkala, just outside Nhulunbuy, is internationally known for bark paintings, promoting the rights of Indigenous Australians, and as the origin of the *yidaki*, or didgeridoo.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] The community of Gunbalanya (previously known as Oenpelli) in Western Arnhem Land is also notable for bark painting.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] The indigenous inhabitants also create temporary sand sculptures as part of their sacred rituals.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] Arnhem Land is also notable for Aboriginal rock art, some examples of which can be found at Ubirr Rock, Injalak Hill, and in the Canon Hill area.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] Some of these record the early years of European explorers and settlers, sometimes in such detail that Martini–Henry rifles can be identified.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] They also depict axes, and detailed paintings of aircraft and ships.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] One remote shelter, several hundred kilometres from Darwin, has a painting of the wharf at Darwin, including building and boats, and Europeans with hats and pipes, some apparently without hands (which they have in their trouser pockets).
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] Near the East Alligator River crossing, a figure was painted of a man carrying a gun and wearing his hair in long pigtails down his back, characteristic of the Chinese labourers brought to Darwin in the late 19th century.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] One Yolngu prehistoric stone arrangement at Macassans Beach near Yirrkala shows the layout of the Makassan *praus* used for *trepang* (sea cucumber) fishing in the area.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] This was a legacy of Yolngu trade links with the people on the Indonesian island of Sulawesi.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] The trading relationship antedated European settlement by some 200 years.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] Aboriginal artists in Arnhem Land are primarily represented by Aboriginal Art Centres, nonprofit, community-owned organisations.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] In East Arnhem Land, primarily Yolngu Matha-speaking artists are promoted by Buku-Larrnggay Mulka in Yirrkala, Bula'bula Arts in Ramingining, Elcho Island Arts and Crafts on Elcho Island, Gapuwiyak Culture and Arts in Gapuwiyak and Milingimbi Art and Culture on Milingimbi Island.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] In Central Arnhem Land, Maningrida Arts & Culture in Maningrida promotes the work of a diverse range of Kuninjku, Burarra, and Gurrgoni artists, amongst others.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] In West Arnhem Land, Injalak Arts in Gunbalanya represents mainly Kunwinjku artists.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] Ngukurr Arts is located on the Roper River in Southern Arnhem Land.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] Art is also produced on the many islands of Arnhem Land, and there are art centres on the Anindilyakwa speaking Groote Eylandt (Anindilyakwa Art) and the Maung speaking Goulburn Islands (Mardbalk Arts & Crafts).
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] Arnhem Land is also known for embracing the homeland movement, sometimes referred to as the outstation movement.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] For many decades prior to 1970, the East Arnhem Land Yolngu people lived on mission stations, such as Yirrkala.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] From April 1972, Yolngu families began moving away, back to their traditional clan lands.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] This was instigated by Yolngu people, before there was government support for the outstation movement.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] The people cleared land for airstrips and built their own houses from local timber, with the help of non-Indigenous people from the mission.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] The elders of the clans aimed to determine their own futures, basing their societies on Yolngu law, while living and raising their children on their lands in a sustainable and self-sufficient way.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] In 1985, Laynhapuy Homelands Aboriginal Corporation (LHAC), an Aboriginal corporation, was established to assist the homelands.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] Homelands are tiny communities where members of related clan groups live on their traditional land, living according to Yolngu rom (law).
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] Homelands also reduce pressure on other Indigenous communities, which are already suffering from problems in the housing, health and education services areas.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] In the early 21st century, a focus from governments about the "viability" of the homelands has caused tensions and uncertainty within the Arnhem Land community.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] In September 2008, then Darwin correspondent for *The Age*, Lindsay Murdoch, wrote: "Elders tell of their fears that Yolngu culture and society will not survive if clans cannot continue to live on and access their land through homelands.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] Gawirrin Gumana AO was a leader of the Dhalwangu clan, renowned for his artwork and knowledge of traditional culture and law.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] Despite facing government concerns and policy confusion, a number of people have developed commercial enterprises that have centred on using the best elements of their homelands.
[src:arnhem-land/arnhem-land] Indigenous tourism ventures incorporating the controlled use of homelands are now showing signs of success for a select number of Yolngu.
